('11209', 71, 'Thin Skin Elastodynamics', 'Journal', 'We present a novel approach for simulating thin hyperelastic skin. Real human skin is only a few millimeters thick. It can stretch and slide over underlying body structures such as muscles, bones, and tendons, revealing rich details of a moving character. Simulating such skin is challenging because it is in close contact with the body and shares its geometry. Despite major advances in simulating elastodynamics of cloth and soft bodies for computer graphics, such methods are difficult to use for simulating thin skin due to the need to deal with non-conforming meshes, collision detection, and contact response. We propose a novel Eulerian representation of skin that avoids all the difficulties of constraining the skin to lie on the body surface by working directly on the surface itself. Skin is modeled as a 2D hyperelastic membrane with arbitrary topology, which makes it easy to cover an entire character or object. Unlike most …', 'Thin skin elastodynamics D Li, S Sueda, DR Neog, DK Pai - ACM Transactions on Graphics (TOG), 2013 Cited by 71 Related articles All 3 versions', '2013/7', 'Duo Li, Shinjiro Sueda, Debanga Raj Neog, Dinesh Pai', 'ACM Transaction on Graphics', 'ACM', 0, 3, 4, 8, 13, 7),
('11210', 17, 'Generating lambertian image with uniform reflectance for endoscope image', 'Journal', 'It is an important topic to recognize polyp from the endoscope image via medical diagnosis. Many approaches have been proposed for the shape recovery for Lambertian reflectance as shape-from-shading problem, while the previous approaches [1][2] treats the actual endoscope image which includes specular reflectance with various color reflectances. Some approaches have been proposed to remove the specular reflectance components.[3] separates diffuse component and specular component from an image taken by a camera with polarizing plate, while [4] tries to generate diffuse component image by removing specular component by taking images of an object from multiple view points.[5] developed a method to convert the original image to Lambertian image using object rotation. Endoscope environment cannot use the polarizing plate, object rotation and multiple images with different view points for the problem of both camera motion and peristaltic movement of object inside body. Previous researches [1][2] proposed approaches to recover 3-D shape of polyp from observed endoscope image with generating diffuse component image by removing specular component.[1][2] has some limitation to the monocular convex object based on the condition of point light source illumination and perspective projection as an extended approach of FMM (Fast Marching Method) to SFS problem proposed by [6]. FMM can be applied to recover the 3-D shape in general but it can be applied to uniform Lambertian reflectance object. So, this paper also aims to generate a uniform diffused reflectance surface from the multicolored image including the …', 'Generating lambertian image with uniform reflectance for endoscope image Y Shimasaki, Y Iwahori, DR Neog, RJ Woodham… - IWAIT2013, 2013 Cited by 17 Related articles All 2 versions', '2013/1', 'Yuki Shimasaki, Yuji Iwahori, Debanga Raj Neog, Robert J Woodham, MK Bhuyan', 'IWAIT2013', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('11211', 74, 'Eyecatch: Simulating visuomotor coordination for object interception', 'Journal', 'We present a novel framework for animating human characters performing fast visually guided tasks, such as catching a ball. The main idea is to consider the coordinated dynamics of sensing and movement. Based on experimental evidence about such behaviors, we propose a generative model that constructs interception behavior online, using discrete submovements directed by uncertain visual estimates of target movement. An important aspect of this framework is that eye movements are included as well, and play a central role in coordinating movements of the head, hand, and body. We show that this framework efficiently generates plausible movements and generalizes well to novel scenarios.', 'Eyecatch: Simulating visuomotor coordination for object interception SH Yeo, M Lesmana, DR Neog, DK Pai - ACM Transactions on Graphics (TOG), 2012 Cited by 74 Related articles All 9 versions', '2012/7/1', 'Sang Hoon Yeo, Martin Lesmana, Debanga R Neog, Dinesh K Pai', 'ACM Transactions on Graphics (TOG)', 'ACM', 0, 4, 5, 5, 6, 14),
