('12850', 0, 'Combined effect of hydroethanolic extracts of Murraya koenigii and Phyllanthus niruri leaves on paracetamol and ethanol-induced toxicity in HepG2 cell line', 'Journal', 'The transversus abdominis plane (TAP) block provides anaesthesia to the anterior abdominal wall. It can be performed using landmark techniques via the Triangle of Petit or using ultrasound guidance. It is an effective tool in postoperative pain management for patients undergoing anterior abdominal wall surgery. It produces a significant reduction in postoperative pain scores, thereby reducing opioid consumption and the incidence of associated side-effects. Cardiopulmonary exercise (CPEX) testing provides a non-invasive method of assessing combined pulmonary, cardiac and circulatory function. It quantifies patient’s functional ability to respond to the increased metabolic demands of major surgery and is commonly used to assess mortality risk preoperatively. The use of CPEX testing to predict postoperative complications is not fully defined. We report the case of a patient with poor functional capacity and a …', 'ase R AM Sherratt, H Wallace, A Banerjee, S Singh, J Hunter - BJMP, 2011 Related articles All 5 versions', '2011/9', 'AM Sherratt, H Wallace, A Banerjee, S Singh, J Hunter', 'BJMP', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12851', 0, 'Assessment of hepatoprotective potential of Solanum xanthocarpum (whole plant) Linn. against isoniazid & rifampicin induced hepatic toxicity in Wistar rats', 'Journal', 'The transversus abdominis plane (TAP) block provides anaesthesia to the anterior abdominal wall. It can be performed using landmark techniques via the Triangle of Petit or using ultrasound guidance. It is an effective tool in postoperative pain management for patients undergoing anterior abdominal wall surgery. It produces a significant reduction in postoperative pain scores, thereby reducing opioid consumption and the incidence of associated side-effects.', 'Use of TAP block in a patient with poor CPEX testing during major abdominal surgery AM Sherratt, H Wallace, A Banerjee, S Singh, J Hunter - British Journal of Medical Practitioners, 2011 Related articles All 4 versions', '2011/9/1', 'AM Sherratt, H Wallace, A Banerjee, S Singh, J Hunter', 'British Journal of Medical Practitioners', 'JMN Medical Education Ltd.', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12852', 0, 'PGPR for sustaining crop productivity under salt stress', 'Journal', 'Materials and Methods Records of 22 cases of large pelvic mass in last five years were analyzed. Their demographic and clinical features were noted, along with imaging features, pre-operative biopsy/cytology, urological interventions, surgical procedure, intra-operative difficulties, complications, staging, adjuvant therapy and outcome. Results There were 14 men and 8 women with median age of 45 years. Presenting symptoms were abdominal mass, pain, LUTS, urinary retention and constipation. Imaging was mostly unable to diagnose organ of origin or nature of tumor. Histopathology revealed pelvic fibromatosis (2), chondrosarcoma (1), liposarcoma (1), hemangioendothelioma (1), lymphangioma (2), fibroleiomyoma (1), leiomyosarcoma (3), schwannoma (4), malignant nerve sheath tumor (MNST)(1), rectal gastro-intestinal stromal tumor (GIST)(1), retrovesical hydatid cysts (3), sacral chordoma (1) and Ewings …', 'UP-03.148 Large Pelvic Masses of Obscure Origin: Urologist\'s Perspective S Kumar, D Sarkar, S Singh - Urology, 2011 All 3 versions', '2011/9/1', 'S Kumar, D Sarkar, S Singh', 'Urology', 'Elsevier', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0);
