('12905', 0, 'URINARY LEVELS OF C-TERMINAL CROSSLINKED TELOPEPTIDE TYPE 1 AS A DIAGNOSTIC INDICATOR OF KNEE OSTEOARTHRITIS', 'Journal', 'Abstracts of free papers presented at the annual meeting of the Obstetric Anaesthetists\' Association, Newcastle, 20 & 21 May Page 1 International Journal of Obstetric Anesthesia 2010 19, S1-S54 doi: 10.1016/j.ijoa.2010.03.014 www.obstetanesthesia.com Abstracts of free papers presented at the annual meeting of the Obstetric Anaesthetists\' Association, Newcastle, 20 & 21 May 2010 (The presenter is underlined) ORAL PRESENTATIONS O1 Accuracy of the pulse oximeter trace and arterial pulsation for measuring blood pressure in healthy volunteers T Strickland , A Sabharwal, SM Yentis S1 O2 Sleek dressings for obstetric epidurals: a microbiological study and survey of current practice MPJ DeVile, P Walsh, ICJW Bowler, R Russell S1 O3 Audit of obstetric anaesthetic response times post introduction of European Working Time Directive (EWTD) compliant rota. L Tompsett, Y Ahmad, H Swales S2 O4 Comparison …', 'Obstetric Anaesthetists\' Association, Newcastle, 20 & 21 May 2010 T Strickland, A Sabharwal, SM Yentis, MPJ DeVile… - International Journal of Obstetric Anesthesia, 2010 Related articles All 2 versions', '2010', 'T Strickland, A Sabharwal, SM Yentis, MPJ DeVile, P Walsh, ICJW Bowler, R Russell, L Tompsett, Y Ahmad, H Swales, R Ramaiah, A Kant, P Groves, M Dresner, B Morton, D Pathak, C Chevannes, P Barclay, V Uppal, RJ Kearns, EM McGrady, LK Kessack, DG Bogod, N Hawkins, L de Lloyd, PW Collins, RE Collis, S Marri, B Munishankar, GA McLeod, GA Corner, S Cochran, T Sreelakshmi, S Jenkins, S Rathinam, R Sashidharan, S Malhotra, A Dharmadasa, S Phillip, A Jepson, C Siegmueller, SL Armstrong, R Fernando, TL Jones, M Columb, S Singh, AP McGlennan, A Dennis, S Simmons, C Carr, M Permezel, C Royse, RM Williamson, J Sivaprakasam, M Purva, R Treadgold, MJ Mackenzie, S Sooranna, MR Johnson, A McDonald, S Mallaiah, MJ Paech, DA Doherty, T Christmas', 'International Journal of Obstetric Anesthesia', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12906', 0, 'PCR Array Based Approach to Find IL-6/STAT3 Mediated Downstream Target Genes Involved in the Skeletal Pathogenesis of Hyper-IGE Syndrome', 'Journal', 'Line X tester analysis was applied for detecting combining ability of nine quantitative characters using 9 lines and 3 testers in fodder oat. Both the general and specific combining ability variances were highly significant for most of the characters studied. It was inferred that non-additive genetic components played predominant role in the expression of these characters. The results on general combining ability revealed that OS-316, OL-1389, UPO-275, NDO-3 and NDO-10 among lines and UPO-212 and Kent among testers were found best combiners for most of the characters studied. On the basis of sca effects with high per se performance the crosses viz., SKO-21× Kent, NDO-10× OS-6, NDO-10× Kent and NDO-3× Kent could be exploited for increasing green forage and grain yield by improving its component traits.', 'Combining ability studies for green forage and grain yield and its components in oat (Avena sativa L.). DN Vishwakarma, CN Ram, SR Vishwakarma… - Agricultural & Biological Research, 2010', '2010', 'DN Vishwakarma, CN Ram, SR Vishwakarma, SS Chauhan, SP Singh', 'Agricultural & Biological Research', 'Young Environment Association', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12907', 0, 'DOES THE CHILD-PUGH SCORE PREDICT ICU SURVIVAL IN THE CRITICALLY ILL PATIENT WITH CHRONIC LIVER FAILURE?', 'Journal', 'The study was conducted on 100 women having more than 60 years of age, selected from two villages representing one rural way of life and another urban way of life from Bhiwani district of Haryana state during the year 2002 to ascertain the level of opinion towards family members, memory changes among old aged women and to establish the relationship between opinion and memory possessed by aged women and their antecedent characteristics. The study reveals that 63% of the aged women were having moderate level of opinion and majority (68%) of respondents had moderate level of memory changes. Comparative analysis of both villages highlights that rural respondents had more unfavourable opinions about family members than urban and slightly more number of urban respondents were suffering from severe level of memory changes than rural. Correlation analysis reveals that out of the nine variables studied four variables, namely, income, land holding, education and caste were found to have positive and significant correlation with opinion formed by the aged women. Only age of the respondents was found to have positive and significant relationship with memory changes.', 'Level of opinion towards family members and memory changes among aged women in Haryana. D Sushila, SP Singh - Haryana Agricultural University Journal of Research, 2010', '2010', 'Dahiya Sushila, SP Singh', 'Haryana Agricultural University Journal of Research', 'CCS Haryana Agricultural University', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12908', 1, 'Hormonal regulation of growth, chlorophyll and protein levels, and the net photosynthesis rate in green bean plants', 'Journal', 'Administration of ivermectin injection@ 0.2 mg/kg b. wt. S/c and doramectin injection@ 0.2 mg/kg b. wt. cured the naturally infected goats with helminth parasites viz. trematade, cestode, nematode worms showing clinical symptoms such as weakness anaemia, rough body coat, wool falling, reduce milk, diarrhoea and emaciation etc. Comparative efficacy of drugs was based on the number of days taken for clinico-parasitological cure and the mean reduction EPG of faeces. During the experiment, ivermectin and doramectin were found to cure helminth parasites in goats due to 100% mean reduction EPG on second week of treatment. No adverse effect such as gastric irritation and photosentization were observed during the study period in any of the goats. The therapeutic management indicates that a single dose of ivermectin or doramectin both@ 0.2 mg/kg b. wt. S/c is equally effective against commonly occurring helminth parasites in goats.', 'Therapeutic management of helminthic infection in goats. P Ved, B Siddiqua, MPS Yadav, SP Singh - Asian Journal of Animal Science, 2010 Cited by 1 Related articles', '2010', 'Prakash Ved, Bano Siddiqua, MPS Yadav, SP Singh', 'Asian Journal of Animal Science', 'Hind Agri-Horticultural Society', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12909', 0, 'Joint cost minimization approach for three echelon supply chain system with multiple buyers under inflation', 'Journal', 'The study deals with the role of vitamin E and selenium at different doses against mastitis in cow of Kanpur region. After screening 70 milch cows, 12 affected with the mastitis were selected and divided into 3 groups T 1, T 2 and T 3 (four in each) for administration of the different doses@ 5 ml E-care se and@ 10 ml E-care se. In T 1 group any medicine or treatment was not applied. The E-care se@ 5 ml was applied in group t 2 and E-care se@ 10 ml was administrated in cow T 3 by intramusculary injections on interval of 7 days. The result of drugs was calculated on 28 day post treatment through biochemical profiles of milk. Administration of E-care se@ 10 ml lowered pH, chloride content and increased the various milk components of the mastitic milk in comparison of small dose@ 5 ml E-care se. Thus, the study indicated that E-care se@ 10 ml was better effective dose for the treatment of mastitis in subclinical cows.', 'Administration of different doses of vitamin E and selenium to control mastitis in cow. P Ved, K Anil, MPS Yadav, SP Singh - Asian Journal of Animal Science, 2010', '2010', 'Prakash Ved, Kumar Anil, MPS Yadav, SP Singh', 'Asian Journal of Animal Science', 'Hind Agri-Horticultural Society', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12910', 1, 'Modeling evolution of a social network using temporalgraph kernels', 'Journal', 'Hedranthera barteri L.(HB) is used in the treatment of painful conditions and oedema amongst its folkloric use. The hexane and ethyl acetate fractions of the root of H. barteri were investigated for anti-nociceptive and antiinflammatory properties and probable mechanism of action. Hot plate, tail flick, formalin-induced oedema and acetic acidinduced writhing tests were employed to investigate the anti-nociceptive activity while the anti-inflammatory activity was investigated using carrageenan-induced paw oedema. Anti-histaminic potential of HB root extracts on the rat peritoneal mast cells (RPMC s) was explored through spectrofluorometric method. The root was screened for its phytochemical components. The HB root contains alkaloids, cardenolides and saponins. HXHBR exhibited higher anti-inflammatory potentials (P< 0.001). HXHBR dose-dependently (P< 0.01) reduced the histamine release from the rat peritoneal mast cells which is comparable with a standard anti-histaminic drug, ketotifen. These results showed that EAHBR and HXHBR possess anti-nociceptive and anti-inflammatory activities, and suggested its mechanism of action through the inhibition of histamine, an inflammatory mediator, usually released during the early phase of allergic responses and chronic phase of inflammatory pain. Flavonoids, alkaloids and/or saponins present in HB root may be responsible for its anti-nociceptive and anti-inflammatory properties.', 'Anti-Histaminic Potential of the Fractions from Hedranthera Barteri [(Hook F.) Pichon] Root in Laboratory Rodents SA Onasanwo, GD Singh, SB Olaleye, S Singh… - Nigerian Journal of Physiological Sciences, 2010 Cited by 1 Related articles All 8 versions', '2010', 'SA Onasanwo, GD Singh, SB Olaleye, S Singh, RK Johri', 'Nigerian Journal of Physiological Sciences', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0),
('12911', 2, 'Interaction Effect of Different Nitrogen and Seed Rate Levels on Sweet Sorghum Feedstuff', 'Journal', 'The prevalence of moniezosis due to Moniezia expansa in goats in Kanpur region of Uttar Pradesh, was studied during February 2008 to January 2009. A total 120 faecal samples from live goats and 120 intestines from slaughtered goats were examined, out of which 14 (11.66%) faecal samples and 10 (8.33%) intestine were found positive for Moniezia expansa. Prevalence of infection was found to be higher during the rainy season both in live (16.66%) and slaughtered (13.33%) goats while lowest in winter season being 6.66% and 3.33%, respectively. Multiple enteritis of varying sizes were observed throughout the intestine of goats due to the presence of the scalices of the parasities, deeply embedded in the mucosa of the intestine. The results of therapeutic trials by using drugs droncit and curaminth indicated 94.89% and 91.57% effective, respectively to cure monieziosis in goats without producing any side effect.', 'Prevalence and chemotherapy of monieziosis in goats. P Ved, B Siddiqua, SP Singh, MPS Yadav - Asian Journal of Animal Science, 2010 Cited by 2 Related articles', '2010', 'Prakash Ved, Bano Siddiqua, SP Singh, MPS Yadav', 'Asian Journal of Animal Science', 'Hind Agri-Horticultural Society', 0, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0),
('12912', 0, 'SwitchNet: Learning to switch for word-level language identification in code-mixed social media text', 'nan', 'Sjogren\'s syndrome is a slowly progressive, inflammatory autoimmune disease affecting primarily the exocrine glands like lacrimal and salivary glands. Histologically, it is characterised by lymphocytic infiltrates that replace functional epithelium and lead to decreased exocrine secretions. The various clinical features of Sjogren\'s syndrome are keratitis, xerostomia and salivary gland enlargement. The condition can be diagnosed by various methods like Schirmer test, sialography, biopsy, etc. and can be treated accordingly.', 'Sjogren\'s Syndrome: A review. P Singh, SK Singh - Medico-Legal Update, 2010 Related articles All 2 versions', '2010/1/1', 'Priyanka Singh, Sanjay Kumar Singh', 'nan', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12913', 3, 'A Hybrid Machine Transliteration Model Based on Multi-source Encoder–Decoder Framework: English to Manipuri', 'Journal', 'A field experiment was undertaken to assess the effect of micronutrients on growth, yield and quality of cauliflower (Brassica oleracea L. var botrytis) cv KCMC-1. The treatment consisted of different micronutrients ie boron, zinc, molybdenum, copper, iron, manganese, their mixture and multiplex. Micronutrients individually and in their combination were prepared in concentration of 0.1%, whereas multiplex was used at 2.5 ml/liter. The spraying was done at 30, 50 and 70 days after transplanting. Experiment was laid out in a randomized block design with three replications. All the standard cultural practices were followed uniformly. Combination of micronutrients (B, Zn, Mo, Cu, Fe, Mn) at 0.1% concentration significantly increased the height of plants, number of leaves/plant, fresh and dry weight of plant, leaf and curds and yield of curd/ha followed by multiplex. Combination of micronutrients exhibited maximum nitrogen and protein content in curds that were statistically at par with multiplex treatment, but the ascorbic acid content was also significantly more.', 'Effect of micronutrients on growth, yield and quality of cauliflower (Brassica oleracea L. var botrytis). AK Singh, SP Singh, V Vishakha - Environment and Ecology, 2010 Cited by 3 Related articles', '2010', 'AK Singh, SP Singh, Verma Vishakha', 'Environment and Ecology', 'MKK Publication', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12914', 1, 'Chart classification: an empirical comparative study of different learning models', 'Journal', 'Farming systems of households as prevailing in western U.P. have been analysed based on a sample of 197 farmers. It was found that the sugurcane based farming systems were predominant in the study area. Live stock, vegetable, cereal and sugarcane were the main source of farm income. The farmers were using surplus fertilizer and chemicals resulting negative marginal value productivity (MVP) on vegetable, cereal and sugarcane based farming system which deserves to be reduced for optimum use. The MVP of credit was found very attractive indicating very good scope to financing agencies to supply agricultural credit to the farmers of the area. Number of dairy animals was found nearly to the optimum (about 3 animals/farm). The farmers employed excess labour about 1300/ha as against the optimum requirement of about 500 man days/ha and there is a large scope to reduce the labour employment in …', 'Identification and Resource Productivities of Existing Farming Systems in Western UP SP Singh, B Gangwar, MP Singh, SP Singh - Progressive Agriculture, 2010 Cited by 1 Related articles All 3 versions', '2010', 'SP Singh, B Gangwar, MP Singh, Satya Pal Singh', 'Progressive Agriculture', 'Society for Recent Development in Agriculture', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12915', 3, 'English-Manipuri Machine Translation: An empirical study of different Supervised and Unsupervised Methods', 'Journal', '(Table 1), at both places Delhi and Cuttack were sown in kharif 2006, with two controls namely ‘IRBB 55’(resistant variety to BLB) and ‘Pusa Basmati 1’(susceptible variety to BLB). Inoculation was done in two stages first in nursery stage and secondly after transplanting in field, to recheck the resistance for bacterial leaf blight. To support the results of test of allelism, screening of the concern genotypes with the respective marker was done for genes Xa21 and xa13 by using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) amplification technique. PCR-based markers pTA 248 for Xa21 and RG 136 for xa13 were used to study the polymorphic relationships. Two sets of 8 genotypes were selected for the study of polymorphism. Genomic DNA was extracted from the young leaves of the plant (after 60 days of transplanting) samples using the standard CTAB method, which is a modification of the methods, developed by Dellaporta et al.(1983) and Murray and Thompson (1980). DNA markers linked to Xa21 and xa13 were based on published results as pTA 248 for Xa21 at 0.1 cM (F-AGACGCGGAAGGGTGGTTCCCGGA, R-GACGCGGTAATCGAAAGATGAAA) and RG136 for x13 at 3.8 cM (F-TCCCAGAAAGCTACTACAGC, R-GCAGACTCCAGTTTGACTTC)(Joseph et al. 2004) were used for the analysis. The PCR reaction mixture were set up in 10 μl volume containing 25 ng template DNA, 25ng each of forward and reverse primers, 0.1 mM dNTPs, 1X PCR buffer (10 mM Tris, pH 8.0, 50 mM KCl and 50 mM ammoniums sulphate), 1.5 mM MgCl2 and 0.2 unit Taq DNA polymerase. To obtain this concentration the following components were added and mixed in 0.2 ml thin …', 'Identification of rice genotypes with high resistance to bacterial leaf blight caused by Xanthomonas oryzae pv oryzae JP Tyagi, T Singh, S Singh, N Goel, SK Pradhan… - Indian J. Agric. Sci, 2010 Cited by 3 Related articles All 5 versions', '2010/1/1', 'JP Tyagi, Tejbir Singh, S Singh, Nitika Goel, SK Pradhan, VP Singh', 'Indian J. Agric. Sci', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12916', 0, 'Manipuri-English Cross-lingual Word Embeddings using a Temporally Aligned Comparable Corpus', 'Journal', 'The effect of Zn on herbage and oil yield of palmarosa (Cymbopogon martinii) was studied in a field experiment. The experiment was laid out under randomized block design (RBD) with six treatments (viz., 0.0, 0.4, 0.5, 0.6, 0.7 and 0.8% Zn and four replications. The foliar application of zinc significantly increased the plant height as compared to control. Similarly, the number of tillers was also significantly increased over control. Maximum herbage yield was associated with 0.7% Zn (735.45 q ha−1) followed by 0.8% Zn (714.91 q ha−1), 0.6% Zn (665.12 q ha−1), 0.5% Zn (625.16 q ha−1) and 0.4% Zn (533.12 q ha−1), respectively. The maximum oil content (0.7%) was registered with control while, the maximum oil yield (441.24 kg ha−1) was obtained with foliar application of 0.7% Zn.', 'Effect of Foliar Application of Zn on Herbage and Oil Yield of Palmarosa (Cymbopogon Martinii) RP Singh, PK Yadav, SN Singh, SKS Chandel… - Agricultural Science Digest, 2010 Related articles All 5 versions', '2010', 'RP Singh, PK Yadav, SN Singh, SKS Chandel, RK Singh', 'Agricultural Science Digest', 'Agricultural Research Communication Centre', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12917', 4, 'Synonymy Expansion Using Link Prediction Methods: A Case Study of Assamese WordNet', 'Journal', 'A field experiment was conducted with three levels of sulphur (0, 20 and 40 kg/ha) and calcium (0, 10 and 20 kg/ha) to study the yield and quality of mustard [Brassica juncea (L.) Czern & Coss.] cv. Varuna as test crop. Results revealed that application of sulphur (S) and calcium (Ca) alone and in combination significantly affected the siliqua, yield, oil content and quality of oil. In each case, the application of S at 40 kg/ha+ Ca at 10 kg/ha was found superior over other treatments. However, the application of Ca at 20 kg/ha with S adversely affected the siliqua number, yield, oil content and quality of oil.', 'Effect of sulphur and calcium on yield and quality of mustard (Brassica juncea). RP Singh, SK Singh, PK Yadav, SN Singh - Journal of oilseeds Research, 2010 Cited by 4 Related articles', '2010', 'RP Singh, SANJAI K Singh, PK Yadav, SN Singh', 'Journal of oilseeds Research', 'Indian Society of Oilseeds Research', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12918', 0, 'Challenges in chart image classification: A comparative study of different deep learning methods', 'Journal', 'A pot culture experiment was conducted to study the effect of Cd on growth, dry matter yield and nutrient composition of Maize (Zea mays L.) and Jwar (Sorghum vulgare L.) under screen house condition. Experiment was conducted with a clay loam soil of pH 8.1, organic carbon 0.32%, CEC 18.40 cmol kg−1 soil and DTPA extractable Cd in traces. Cadmium was applied @ 0, 2.5, 5, 10 and 20 mg kg−1 soil as CdCl2. Maize and jwar were grown for 45 days and after harvesting plants were analysed for Cd, Zn and Mn using AAS. The phytotoxicity symptoms in maize and jwar were apparent after 25 days of sowing and observed only for Cd at 20 mg kg−1 soil. Increasing levels of soil applied Cd significantly decreased the dry matter yield of both the crops under study. The content of Cd in crops increased significantly with increasing rates of soil applied Cd. Maximum concentration was found for 20 mg kg−1 soil with an …', 'Effect of Cd on growth, dry matter yield and nutrient composition of maize and jwar RP Singh, SKS Chandel, SN Singh, PK Yadav - Indian Journal of Scientific Research, 2010 Related articles All 2 versions', '2010', 'RP Singh, SKS Chandel, SN Singh, PK Yadav', 'Indian Journal of Scientific Research', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12919', 2, 'Manipuri-English machine translation using comparable corpus', 'Journal', 'Of late, increasing attention is being paid to harness the potential benefits from renewable sources of plant nutrients. Agriculture, devoid of recycled organic wastes, is facing a disorder in physico-chemical and biological properties of the soil. Composting is the best method to utilize huge quantum of refuse generated as a renewable source of plant nutrients if properly managed. However, the use of organic manures is facing a serious problem mainly due to its low nutrient content and poor rate of mineralization. This paper analyses the attempts made to utilize industrial and farm wastes, their enrichment with minerals and bio-activators and effect of micronutrients for sustained rice productivity.', 'Utilisation of industrial and farm wastes with minerals and bio-activators for sustained rice productivity in eastern Uttar Pradesh. BS Shekhawat, S Yogeshwar, SP Singh, RN Meena… - Indian Journal of Fertilisers, 2010 Cited by 2 Related articles', '2010', 'BS Shekhawat, Singh Yogeshwar, SP Singh, RN Meena, Y Singh, Singh Kalyan', 'Indian Journal of Fertilisers', 'Fertiliser Association of India', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1),
('12920', 3, 'Empirical study of sentiment analysis tools and techniques on societal topics', 'nan', 'nan', 'Studies on suitability of cultivars and dates of picking of berries for preparation of imitation cherry and jelly from karonda (carissa carandas l.) fruits S Singh - 2010 Cited by 3 Related articles', '2010', 'S Singh', 'nan', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 2),
('12921', 0, 'Predicting emotion dynamics sequence on Twitter via deep learning approach', 'Journal', 'A study was conducted in Aligarh district of Uttar Pradesh. The study covered ten villages and 300 respondents belong to small categories. The study aim to generalize socio-economic profile of the farmers and utilization of fertilizer technology in the area under study. The study highlighted that majority (63.33%) of the small farmers were in 31 to 45 year age group and living in pucca house. The majority (87.15%) respondents were educated up to high school there annual income range from 10, 000 to 25, 000 and member of atleast one organization they living in nuclear family system. Only 45.33 per cent respondent adopted the fertilizer technology in the range of 76–100 per cent level of adoption. In the selected area maximum overall adopters were belong to medium adoption categories with their nitrogenous, phosphatic and potassic fertilizers adoption i. e. 44.67, 41.00 and 04.67 per cent respectively. The …', 'Relative Influence of Socio-Personal Characteristics and Utilization of Fertilizer Technology in Wheat Cultivation SP Singh, J Singh, PK Tyagi, R Kumar - Indian Journal of Extension Education, 2010 Related articles All 2 versions', '2010', 'SP Singh, Jogender Singh, PK Tyagi, Rupendra Kumar', 'Indian Journal of Extension Education', 'The Indian Society of Extension Education', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12922', 6, 'Sentiment analysis of tweets using heterogeneous multi-layer network representation and embedding', 'Journal', 'The effect of co-existing mycoflora with Aspergillus flavus was observed on wheat grains for its influence on anatoxin B1 and G1 production. All 17 types of associations of different fungal species inhibited aflatoxin B1 production at different levels (48.21–90.23%). Among the screened co-existing moulds, the minimum inhibition in aflatoxin B1 production was caused by A. japonicus and the maximum inhibition was caused by Penicillium citrinum (90.23% and Trichoderma viride (90.15%). However, aflatoxin G1 production was completely inhibited by Aspergillus fumigatus, A. niger, Candida albicans, Chaetomium globosum, Penicillium citrinum, Trichoderma viride and a toxigenic strain of Aspergillus flavus. These results suggest the potential of co-existing moulds in biological control against pre and post harvest aflatoxin contamination of agricultural commodities.', 'Effect of some co-existing moulds on aflatoxin production in wheat grains under competitive environment T Misra, J Dixit, S Singh - Indian Journal of Scientific Research, 2010 Cited by 6 Related articles All 4 versions', '2010', 'Tanuja Misra, Jayendra Dixit, S Singh', 'Indian Journal of Scientific Research', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12923', 1, 'Towards implementing fast and scalable network intrusion detection system using entropy based discretization technique', 'nan', 'The Expert Committee on Specifications for Pharmaceutical Preparations works towards clear, independent and practical standards and guidelines for the quality assurance of medicines. Standards are developed by the Committee through worldwide consultation and an international consensus-building process. The following new guidelines were adopted and recommended for use: good practices for pharmaceutical quality control laboratories; supplementary guidelines for active pharmaceutical ingredients; good manufacturing practices for pharmaceutical products containing hazardous substances; good manufacturing practices for sterile pharmaceutical products; good distribution practices for pharmaceutical products; guidelines on the requalification of prequalified dossiers: and guidelines for the preparation of a contract research organization master file.', 'WHO Expert Committee on specifications for pharmaceutical preparations. SA Bawazir, JM Caudron, TG Dekker… - 2010 Cited by 1 Related articles All 2 versions', '2010', 'SA Bawazir, JM Caudron, TG Dekker, NM Guerrero Rivas, J Hoogmartens, J Shaohong, JH Miller, JA Molzon, M Treebamroog, EW Biwota, I Addae-Mensah, HG Kristensen, ML Rabouhans, JL Robert, S Singh, R Tribe, GJ Farquharson, S Mills, E Pelkonen, B Schumauser, D Smith, A Speitzhofer, PS Jakobsen, J Daviaud, A Lodi, P Kozarewicz, MG Beatrice, N Cappuccino, B Suffolk, AJ Hoek, C Anquez-Traxler, M FitzGerald, M Vallender, HS Kim, SJ Lee, KA Russo, CF Etienne, HV Hogerzeil, S Rägo, S Kopp, C Mendy, R Balocco, A Gould, R Kuwana, M Mehmandoust, D Mubangizi, J Saboartova, I Streipa, WZ Worku, H Yin, A van Zyl, S Azatyan, J Hetzke, Y Maruyama, C Ondari, RF Théry, DJ Wood', 'nan', 'University of Nairobi', 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12924', 0, 'Effect of class imbalance in heterogeneous network embedding: An empirical study', 'Journal', 'Chronic stable angina is a debilitating illness affecting millions worldwide. Considerable progress has been made over the last 30 years in understanding its pathogenesis. Conventional anti-anginal drugs such as nitrates, β-blockers and calcium channel blockers effect heart rate, blood pressure, pre-load and contractility and thus reduce the oxygen demand. Ranolazine is a new anti-anginal drug approved by the US-FDA for use either as an add-on therapy and now even as a monotherapy. It inhibits the late sodium currents, thereby maintaining sodium–calcium homeostasis and preventing ischaemia induced diastolic dysfunction. Ranolazine does not affect the heart rate, BP and ionotropic state. Antianginal benefits of Ranolazine have been confirmed by various trials (MARISA, CARISA, ERICA, MERLIN TIMI 36 etc.) in addition it exerts anti-arrhythmic effect in acute NSTEMI. Although it prolongs QTc interval but no case of Torsade de pointes has been observed. It significantly lowers HbA1C in diabetics, which represents potential for clinical benefit. Ivabradineis a pure heart rate lowering agent acting by inhibiting the funny current (If) in the SA node. It doesn’t affect blood pressure, myocardial contractility, intra cardiac conduction or ventricular repolarisation. Clinical trials (BEAUTIFUL, ASSOCIATE etc.) endorse the concept of pure heart rate lowering as a strategy for improving exercise capacity in patients with stable angina,', 'RANOLAZINE AND IVABRADINE-THEIR CURRENT USE HK Rao, RS Gupta, SR Singh - Medicine, 2010 Related articles', '2010', 'Harbir Kaur Rao, RS Gupta, SR Singh', 'Medicine', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12925', 1, 'Emotion dynamics of public opinions on twitter', 'Journal', 'Salmonella enterica are widespread in humans and animals worldwide and are of increasing public health concern. A total of 1000 samples comprising 450 human and 550 animal clinical samples collected between January, 2008 and November, 2009 from different clinics located in Bareilly city of Uttar Pradesh, North India were subjected for isolation and identification of Salmonella employing standard bacteriological methods. Antimicrobial sensitivity pattern was studied against 10 drugs. Twenty seven (2.7%) isolates belonging to 7 serovars (S. Paratyphi B var java, S. Typhimurium, S. Isangi, S. Tshiongwe, S. Bsilla, S. Labadi) and rough type were isolated from 1,000 human and animal clinical cases. The most prevalent serotype was Salmonella Paratyphi B var Java both among human and animal isolates. Five uncommon serotypes viz., S. Isangi, S. Tshiongwe, S. Saintpaul, S. Bsilla and S. Labadi were recorded among the animal clinical isolates. Isolation rates from human and animal cases were 1.77% and 3.45%, respectively.', 'Predominance of Paratyphi B var Java serotype among human and animal clinical isolates of Salmonella in north India. S Singh, RK Agarwal, SC Tiwari, K Kumar, P Nambiar - Journal of Veterinary Public Health, 2010 Cited by 1 Related articles', '2010', 'S Singh, RK Agarwal, SC Tiwari, K Kumar, P Nambiar', 'Journal of Veterinary Public Health', 'Indian Association of Veterinary Public Health Specialists', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12926', 2, 'SHE: Sentiment hashtag embedding through multitask learning', 'nan', 'Employee Creativity is a topic of great importance for present day management.‘Local leaders’(ie employee supervisors) are one of the most immediate and potent influencers of employee creativity. Few studies have, however, focused on understanding how these ‘local leaders’ influence employee creativity. While the research exploring the relationship between leadership styles and creativity is scant, there exists even less research analyzing the impact of specific leader behaviors on employee creativity. Moreover, there exists a dearth of studies analyzing the influence of leaders on employee perceptual and psychological processes and eventually their creative performance. Taking leave from the popular two-factor classifications of leadership like transformational-transactional and consideration-initiating structure, the first part of the study identifies important supervisory behaviors that impact employee creativity. The second part presents work motivation (intrinsic and extrinsic motivations), positive psychological capital (self-efficacy, hope, optimism and resilience) and justice perceptions (distributive, procedural and interactional justice perceptions) as important mediating variables for the leadershipcreativity relationship. The paper identifies patterns of behaviors that can influence each of the proposed mediating variables. The paper is conceptual in nature and provides seeds for future research.', 'Impact of leader behaviors on employee creativity: exploring the role of work motivation, positive psychological capital and justice perceptions V Gupta, S Singh - 2010 Cited by 2 Related articles', '2010', 'VISHAL Gupta, S Singh', 'nan', 'Working paper series, Indian Institute of Management', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12927', 0, 'Network sampling using k-hop random walks for heterogeneous network embedding', 'Journal', 'Agriculture in developing countries heavily dependent on manual labour and major contribution comes from womens, Agriculture is physically ardous occupation and exposes the workers to various risk factors associated with musculo skeletal disorders. Hence, in present study work stress caused due to four selected farm operation (weeding, harvesting, carrying and winnowing) were assessed through 5 point scale and task frequency chart. Fifty farm women were selected randomly from student’s farm and seed technology farm of CSAUA &T., Kanpur. Findings suggests that carrying is most stressful activity among all selected farm operations. It may because of carrying requires various kind of tasks involving body different kind of motions against the gravitational force.', 'A Comparative study of work stress of the farm women Caused by selected farm activities D CHAUHAN, J KHATOON, SP SINGH - THE JOURNAL OF RURAL AND AGRICULURAL …, 2010 Related articles All 2 versions', '2010', 'DEEPALI CHAUHAN, JAHIDA KHATOON, SP SINGH', 'THE JOURNAL OF RURAL AND AGRICULURAL RESEARCH', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12928', 2, 'Prioritized Named Entity Driven LDA for Document Clustering', 'Journal', 'Rainfed lowlands are the major rice (Oryza sativa L.) ecosystem in eastern India spread over 13 million ha, and its productivity in this region is around 1.5 tonnes/ha. Early drought and flood cause delayed planting, resulting in further yield decline. More than 50% of rainfed lowland rice, transplanting is frequently delayed (Mackill et al. 1996). Yield stability is another major problem of rainfed lowland ecosystem. Traditional rice cultivars grown in rainfed lowlands provide stable protection against flood, drought and delayed planting-related problems, but they are less responsive to favourable environments or higher inputs. Drought or flooding often makes it impossible to transplant at optimum age of seedlings. Rice farmers need improved genotypes with better yields and stability under delayed planting conditions across environments. The choice of suitable breeding procedure depends upon the relative magnitude of different kinds of genes and an understanding of the mode of inheritance of complex quantitative characters. Generation means analysis used to estimate the components of genetic variance which provides information about the predominant type of gene action for the different traits under improvement. This analysis is one of the several tools used in estimating additive, dominance and epistatic variations. Literature survey revealed that voluminous work has been done for gene action of various traits in rice (Singh et al. 2004). But reports on lowland rice is very scanty. Furthermore, work on gene action under delayed planting condition is not available. Therefore, the present investigation was undertaken to know the additive, dominance …', 'Genetic analysis of agromorphologic traits under normal and delayed planting in rainfed lowland rice (Oryza sativa) S Singh, SK Pradhan, NK Singh, AK Singh, PK Singh… - Indian Journal of Agricultural Sciences, 2009 Cited by 2 Related articles All 4 versions', '2009/12/1', 'S Singh, SK Pradhan, NK Singh, AK Singh, PK Singh, JP Tyagi, VN Singh, R Chandra', 'Indian Journal of Agricultural Sciences', 'Indian Council of Agricultural Research', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12929', 1, 'On applying meta-path for network embedding in mining heterogeneous DBLP network', 'Conference', 'Feeders form a critical part of automated assembly lines. Along with feeding from a bulk supply, they also convert the randomness of parts into a flow in a geometrical pattern and deliver them at a predetermined rate. This paper mathematically analyses a reciprocating-fork hopper feeder. This system supplies headed parts like bolts and rivets in an upright configuration to the delivery chute through a pneumatically-actuated reciprocating fork which picks up the parts from a rotating bowl. The feed rate performance of the feeder is analysed for three parameters: part population, rate of reciprocation of fork and speed of rotation of bowl. The Design of Experiments (DOE) is done using 2 3 full-factorial method. A mathematical model is formulated using Design Expert ® software, to investigate the significance of individual parameters as well as interactions amongst them. Adequacy of the model to predict the performance …', 'Mathematical performance analysis of a reciprocating-fork hopper feeder SP Singh, S Ghosh, P Khanna - 2009 IEEE Student Conference on Research and …, 2009 Cited by 1 Related articles All 2 versions', '2009/11/16', 'Sarv Parteek Singh, Shramana Ghosh, Pradeep Khanna', '2009 IEEE Student Conference on Research and Development (SCOReD)', 'IEEE', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12930', 1, 'Influence of social conversational features on language identification in highly multilingual online conversations', 'Journal', 'In this paper, we propose a new security protocol which is styled hierarchical access control-based proxy signature (HACBPS). In hierarchical access control, upper security level users can access some secret information hold by lower security level users, but reverse is not allowed. Whereas in proxy signature, on behalf of the original signer, proxy signer can generate the signature on an arbitrary message. In our protocol, an upper security level user (considered as original signer) can delegate his signing right for signature generation on an arbitrary message to a lower security level user (considered as proxy signer) and the proxy signer can generate proxy signature on behalf of the original signer. In HACBPS, each user in a hierarchy holds two secret keys: one key can be accessed by upper security level users and other one is not accessible to any other user.', 'HACBPS: a hierarchical access control-based proxy signature D Giri, J Dalal, PD Srivastava, SR Singh - International Journal of Recent Trends in Engineering, 2009 Cited by 1 Related articles All 4 versions', '2009/11/1', 'Debasis Giri, Jiban Dalal, PD Srivastava, Sanasam Ranbir Singh', 'International Journal of Recent Trends in Engineering', 'Academy Publisher', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('12931', 5, 'Word level language identification in Assamese-Bengali-Hindi-English code-mixed social media text', 'Journal', 'Quality of Service (QoS) support in Mobile Ad-hoc NETworks (MANETs) is a challenging task. The major challenge in ad hoc networks lies in adapting multicast communication to environments, where mobility is unlimited and failures are frequent. Such problems increase the delays and decrease the throughput. To meet these challenges, authors have proposed bandwidth control management (BWCM) model to improve the QoS performance [9] by minimized end-to-end delay.', 'Dynamic Behavior of Bandwidth Control Management in Mobile Ad-Hoc Network K Manoj, SC Sharma, SP Singh - Proceedings of the World Congress on Engineering …, 2009 Cited by 5 Related articles All 2 versions', '2009/10/20', 'Kumar Manoj, SC Sharma, SP Singh', 'Proceedings of the World Congress on Engineering and Computer Science', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
