('13027', 0, 'Effect of class imbalance in heterogeneous network embedding: An empirical study', 'Journal', 'The present study was undertaken to investigate the effect of grainless ration in relation to body weight changes, dry matter intake and feed conversion efficiency. Eighteen male Murrah buffalo calves (6-9 months old) were randomly distributed into 3 groups, and fed different isonitrogenous concentrate mixtures (I, II and III) to meet their energy and protein requirement. Concentrate mixture I (control) had maize, while in concentrate II and III maize was replaced with rice polish and deoiled rice polish, respectively. Wheat straw was fed ad libitum. Experimental feeding was done for a period of 120 days. The total body weight gain and average daily gain were significantly (P< 0.05) lower in group III in comparison to control group. The total dry matter intake in group I, II and III was 553.27±4.25, 516.70±9.36, 442.46±4.44, respectively. The feed conversion efficiency (FCE) was ranged between 9.41±0.62 (group I) to 9.93±0.33 (group III) showed no significant difference and indicated that feeding of grainless ration had no adverse effect on FCE. Thus it can be concluded that rice polish based diet was capable of supplying maintenance and growth requirement of Murrah buffalo calves.', 'Effect of grainless ration on dry matter intake, growth and feed conversion efficiency in Murrah buffalo calves. V Srivastava, PS Niranjan, SP Singh, S Jaswant - Veterinary Practitioner, 2007', '2007', 'V Srivastava, PS Niranjan, SP Singh, Singh Jaswant', 'Veterinary Practitioner', 'Veterinary Practitioner, c/o Dr. AK Gahlot', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
