('13042', 5, 'Automatic pause marking for speech synthesis', 'Journal', 'Previous research revealed that the problem of discovering a complete set of frequent itemsets from a large database can be reduced to the problem of discovering the frequent closed itemsets, and this process results in a much smaller set of itemsets without information loss. This article is based on the observation that the set of all itemsets can be grouped into non-overlapping clusters such that each cluster is identified by a unique closed tidset. It is also found that there is only one closed itemset in each cluster and it is the superset of all itemsets with the same support. Therefore, the problem of discovering closed itemsets can be further considered as the problem of clustering the set of itemsets and then identifying each cluster by a unique closed tidset. This article presents CloseMiner, a new algorithm for discovering all frequent closed itemsets by grouping the set of itemsets into non-overlapping clusters …', 'An algorithm for discovering the frequent closed itemsets in a large database N Gourakishwar Singh, S Ranbir Singh, AK Mahanta… - Journal of Experimental & Theoretical Artificial …, 2006 Cited by 5 Related articles', '2006/12/1', 'Ningthoujam Gourakishwar Singh, Sanasam Ranbir Singh, Anjana K Mahanta, Bhanu Prasad', 'Journal of Experimental & Theoretical Artificial Intelligence', 'Taylor & Francis Group', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13043', 0, 'Effect of planting date on incidence of early blight (Alternaria Solanai) and yield of potato due to climate change', 'Journal', 'Methods 15 adult patients planned for cystoscopy underwent urodynamic study (UDS) at baseline and 30 minutes after administration of Tramadol 100mg (10 mg/ml 0.9% saline) in lumbar (L3-L4) epidural space. UDS consisted of filling cystometry, pressure-flow study and pelvic floor electromyography (EMG). Subsequently, the patients underwent cystoscopy for the respective indication and kept under observation for monitoring adverse effect, if any. Results After injection of tramadol, a significant increase was observed in bladder capacity (375.4±180.8 ml vs. 423.4±206.7 ml; p= 0.007) and compliance (60.1±51.5 ml/cmH2O vs. 83.0±63.0 ml/cmH2O; p= 0.011) without a significant change in filling pressure (22.5±13.2 vs. 24.1±15.1 cmH2O; p= 0.576). Filling sensations were delayed significantly as depicted by significant rise in volume at first sensation, normal desire, strong desire and urgency (p= 0.028, 0.001, 0 …', 'UP-01.90: Effect of lumbar-epidural administration of tramadol on neurophysiology of bladder S Singh, M Agarwal, Y Batra, A Mandal - Urology, 2006 All 3 versions', '2006/11/1', 'S Singh, M Agarwal, Y Batra, A Mandal', 'Urology', 'Elsevier', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13044', 2, 'Automatic syllabification for manipuri language', 'Journal', 'Rice (Oryza safiva L.)-wheat (Triticum aestivum L. emend. Fiori & Paol) cropping system in India is being cultivated on an area of 10.5 million ha which contributes approximately 25% in the national food grain production (Gupta 2003). Use of nitrogenous fertilizers, viz urea has played key a role in enhancing the rice-wheat production, yet its use-efficiency in rice is only 3040% or even less (Prasad and Power 1995). Besides, fertilizer use has been sensitive to price relationship, on the other front, soil health and productivity is becoming more important in present paradigm. Therefore, we need fertilizers, which are not only cost effective but also maintain soil health favourably. This could be possible by two ways, firstly, using the inorganic fertilizers which can meet the crop nutrient demand for entire season through single application and secondly, supplementing inorganic fertilizer demand with proper proportions of organic sources. Keeping in view these concerns, present investigations were undertaken to study the effect of prilled urea, biogas slurry, neem oil-treated urea sources and their combinations in various proportions on productivity and economics of rice-wheat cropping system. A field experiment was conducted during the rainy and winter seasons of 1999-2000 and 2000-2001 on sandy clayloam soils of the research farm at Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi (2g040\'N latitude, 77\' 1OYE longitude and 228.6 m altitude). The experimental field was slightly alkaline, having pH 7.8 with organic carbon0. 53%(Walkley and Black 1934), total nitrogen 0.052%(Modified Kjeldahl method, Jackson 1958), available nitrogen 2 18 kgha …', 'Productivity and economics of rice (Oryza sativa)-wheat (Triticum aestivum) cropping system as influenced by neem oil-treated urea and biogas slurry NM Bharde, YS Shivay, S Singh, D Kumar - Indian Journal of Agricultural Sciences, 2006 Cited by 