('13093', 0, 'Organic Farming: A need of sustainable agriculture', 'Journal', 'Burkina Faso has three major rice ecologies—upland (10% of land area with 5% of the country’s rice production), irrigated (23% of area and 53% of production), and rainfed lowland (67% of area and42% ofproduction)(Sié1999). Rainfed lowland is the major rice ecologyinthecountry, combining the characteristics of upland and irrigated systems. The declining and unpredictable rainfall pattern has led to the disappearance of traditional Oryza sativa cultivars. Consequently, farmers now cultivate O. glaberrima, which has good agronomic traits—ie, acceptable grain quality, plant vigor, and resistance to major biotic and abiotic stresses (Pham 1992, Besançon 1993, Adeyemi and Vodouhe 1996, Sie 1999). To meet the demand of rice farmers and consumers, the rice research program in Burkina Faso started evaluatingintra-andinterspecific lowland progenies obtained from WARDA, Senegal, in 2000. This study aimed …', 'Pest science and management D Mukherjee, RP Singh, S Youpensuk, N Yimyam… - International Rice Research Notes, 2005 Related articles', '2005', 'D Mukherjee, RP Singh, S Youpensuk, N Yimyam, B Rerkasem, B Dell, RA Singh, RB Singh, G Singh, S Singh, A Ghosh, BN Singh, DP Biradar, Nagappa Shivakumar, MA Basavannep, KS Gangwar, SK Sharma, OK Tomar, DK Pandey, MS Islam, GJU Ahmed, AW Julfiquar, M Farooq, SMA Basra, N Ahmad, RDS Yadav, GR Singh, P Jeyaprakash, S Robin, SK Ganesh, M Subramanian, A Palchamy, P Balasubramaniyan, S Raghuraman, YS Johnson, Thangaraj Edward, RB Yadaw, B Chaudhary, NP Adhikari, T Akhtar, BV Ingale, BD Waghmode, A Arora, S Saxena, S Geetha, S Mohandas, SE Naina Mohammed, S Anthoniraj, Diadema Martinez, SK Behera, Nand Ram, RK Singh, CV Singh, VD Shukla', 'International Rice Research Notes', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
