('13115', 1, 'Joint cost minimization approach for three echelon supply chain system with multiple buyers under inflation', 'Conference', 'The problem of mining complete set of frequent itemsets can be reduced to the problem of mining frequent closed itemsets, which results in a much smaller set of itemsets without information loss. In this paper, we discuss an algorithm to mine frequent closed itemsets (FCI) using conditional frequent pattern tree called CFP-tree. Mining FCI from CFP-tree is simply tracing of prefix nodes, which is a straight forward method. The main advantage of this method lies in the used of simple data structures and less computations in mining FCI. From the experimental comparisons, we find that our method outperforms Apriori and Mafia and equally performs CHARM.', 'Mining frequent closed itemsets using conditional frequent pattern tree SR Singh, BK Patra, D Giri - Proceedings of the IEEE INDICON 2004. First India …, 2004 Cited by 1 Related articles', '2004/12/20', 'Sanasam Ranbir Singh, BK Patra, Debasis Giri', 'Proceedings of the IEEE INDICON 2004. First India Annual Conference, 2004.', 'IEEE', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13116', 18, 'Modeling evolution of a social network using temporalgraph kernels', 'Conference', 'Web contains a large collection of heterogeneous documents. As a result, finding set of related pages from Web is currently facing one of the most crucial problems. The low precision Web search engines like Excite, Alta Vista etc. coupled with the ranked list presentation make it harder for users to find the information they are looking for. In this paper, we have proposed a methodology to cluster related pages using co-citations without manual study and/or predefined categories. These clusters are used to classify random pages in the Universe.', 'An algorithm for automatic web-page clustering using link structures D Mukhopadhyay, SR Sing - Proceedings of the IEEE INDICON 2004. First India …, 2004 Cited by 18 Related articles All 4 versions', '2004/12/20', 'Debajyoti Mukhopadhyay, Sanasam Ranbir Sing', 'Proceedings of the IEEE INDICON 2004. First India Annual Conference, 2004.', 'IEEE', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13117', 1, 'Interaction Effect of Different Nitrogen and Seed Rate Levels on Sweet Sorghum Feedstuff', 'Journal', 'Data were collected on the molybdenum and trace element concentration in human blood plasma from 110 residents of Uttar Pradesh. The overall mean value for the molybdenum content of human blood plasma was 0.018 ppm. Most of the individual values for molybdenum in blood plasma fell within the narrow range of 0.007 to 0.033 ppm, yet there was evidence for geographic variations in the molybdenum content of milk collected from various cities.', 'Trace metal levels (Cu, Fe, Mn, Mo, Ni and Zn) in human blood plasma in Uttar Pradesh R Pandey, R Mishra, SP Singh - JOURNAL OF ADVANCED ZOOLOGY, 2004 Cited by 1 Related articles', '2004/12/1', 'R Pandey, R Mishra, SP Singh', 'JOURNAL OF ADVANCED ZOOLOGY', 'ASSN ADVAN ZOOLOGY', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13118', 1, 'SwitchNet: Learning to switch for word-level language identification in code-mixed social media text', 'Journal', 'KS00WGRC44 (Reg. no. GP-744, PI 632343) is a hard red winter wheat (Triticum aestivurn L.) with resistance to leaf rust [caused by Puccinia triticina Eriks.= P. recondita Roberge ex Desmaz. f. sp. tritici (Eriks. & E. Henn.) DM Henderson] developed cooperatively by the ARS, USDA, the Kansas Agricultural Experiment Station, and the Wheat Genetics Resource Center. It was released as germplasm August 2000. KS00WGRC44 is a B [C. sub. 2][F. sub. 6]-derived line with the pedigree\'TAM 107\'* 3/TA 1715. TAM 107 is a hard red winter wheat cultivar (Porter et al., 1987), and TA 1715 is a leaf rust resistant accession of Aegilops tauschii Coss. collected in Iran. The [F. sub. 1] hybrids between TAM 107 and TA 1715 were produced in the greenhouse in 1995 using TAM 107 as the female parent.[F. sub. 1] embryos were rescued on artificial media (Gill and Raupp, 1987) and [F. sub. 1] plants were backcrossed as …', 'Registration of KS00WGRC44 leaf rust-resistant hard red winter wheat germplasm GL Brown-Guedira, AK Fritz, BS Gill, S Singh, TS Cox - Crop science, 2004 Cited by 1 Related articles All 7 versions', '2004/3/1', 'GL Brown-Guedira, AK Fritz, BS Gill, S Singh, TS Cox', 'Crop science', 'Crop Science Society of America', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13119', 0, 'A Hybrid Machine Transliteration Model Based on Multi-source Encoder–Decoder Framework: English to Manipuri', 'nan', 'Cuphea (Fam. Lythraceae) is main natural plant source of medium chain fatty acids (C8:0- C 14:0). Cuphea procumbens is rich source of capric acid (C10:0) and a study was made in this species to know the different genetic systems involved in the inheritance of fruits/ raceme following 6 parents half diallel in F1 and F2 generations. The high value of dominance component (H1) accompanied with degree of dominance (H1/D)0.5 and graphical analysis indicated non additive gene action in both the generations. The difference of dominant components (H1-H2) is very close indicating the proportional distribution of positive and negative alleles at loci governing the fruits / raceme. Parents distributed around regression line on Wr-Vr graph in four distinct groups showing much diversity for this trait. On the basis of high per se and significant gca effect of parents NBC-03 and NBC-01 were found best in both the generations. In general hybrids viz: NBC-01 × NBC-03, NBC-01 × NBC-25 and NBC-03 × NBC-20 which had high mean performance also had significant sca effects and heterosis.', 'Genetics of Fruits/Raceme in Cuphea procumbens SP Singh, M Singh - 2004', '2004', 'SP Singh, Meenakshi Singh', 'nan', 'NISCAIR-CSIR, India', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13120', 0, 'Chart classification: an empirical comparative study of different learning models', 'Journal', 'An experiment was conducted during 1998-99 and 1999-2000 to study degree of heterosis in creeping waxweed (Cuphea procumbens Ort.) for seed yield, oil content and other component traits. Analysis of variance showed significant differences among the parents and crosses. Significant positive heterosis for seed yield/plant to the magnitude of 39.37%(\'NBC 20\'×\'NBC 30\'), followed by 23.85%(\'NBC 01\'×\'NBC 25\') and 23.8%(\'NBC 01\'×\'NBC 03\') and for oil content only 6.92%(\'NBC 01\'×\'NBC 03\') over better parent was observed. For component traits, maximum heterosis was noticed to the extent of50. 28%(\'NBC 20\'×\'NBC 30\') for fruits/plant, 20.46%(\'NBC 01\'×\'NBC12\') for branches/plant, 20.44%(\'NBC 01\'×\'NBC 25\') for plant height, 23.89%(\'NBC 01\'×\'NBC 12\') for fruits/raceme, 18.46%(\'NBC 12\'×\'NBC 30\') for seeds/fruits and 6.10%(\'NBC 20\'×\'NBC 25\') for days to flower. Per-se performance of hybrids was in general associated with heterotic response. Parental cluster separated by low to intermediate D 2 exhibitedhigh heterosis.', 'Heterosis in creeping waxweed (Cuphea procumbens) SP Singh, M SINGH - Indian journal of agricultural science, 2004', '2004', 'SP Singh, Meenakshi SINGH', 'Indian journal of agricultural science', 'Indian Council of Agricultural Research', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
