('13232', 3, 'Towards implementing fast and scalable network intrusion detection system using entropy based discretization technique', 'Journal', 'Fusarium coccophilum [Nectria flammea] was recorded as a fungal pathogen of the sugarcane whitefly, Aleurolobus barodensis from Dhule and Pune areas of Maharashtra. The infection level during rainy season varied from 2.2 to 12.8%. Its pathogenicity both to nymphs and pupae was confirmed. This is the first report of F. coccophilum on sugarcane whitefly.', 'Occurrence of Fusarium coccophilum (Desm.) Wollenw. & Reinking on sugarcane whitefly, Aleurolobus barodensis (Maskell)(Homoptera: Aleyrodidae). J Sunil, PS Kumar, SP Singh - Journal of Biological Control, 2000 Cited by 3 Related articles', '2000', 'Joshi Sunil, P Sreerama Kumar, SP Singh', 'Journal of Biological Control', 'Society for Biocontrol Advancement', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13233', 5, 'Effect of class imbalance in heterogeneous network embedding: An empirical study', 'Journal', 'Heterosis in opium poppy (Papaver somniferum) was studied for opium yield, seed yield and its 5 component characters in 10 hybrids obtained from 5 diverse parents half diallel. Analysis of variance showed significant differences among the parents and crosses. Greater variability in the parents indicated the possibility of getting higher heterosis in these crosses. None of the crosses showed uniformity in the heterosis for yield components. However, significant positive heterosis to the magnitude of 102.06%(IS-16× Early) followed by 100%(IS-16× Aphuri) for opium yield and 150.29%(Apium× Early) followed by 42.86%(NBRI-5× Early) for seed yield over better parent was observed. The lowest yielding parents in general, produced the highest yielding progeny perhaps, due to their favourable alleles exclusively of the recessive additive genes. The heterosis study comeincingly raised the possibility that a gene introgression breeding strategically based upon the diverse parents like IS-16, Aphuri and Early would ensure multifold increase in yield traits in opium poppy.', 'Heterosis study revealing the existence of introgression populations in opium poppy. S Sudhir, S Neelam, SP Singh - Journal of Medicinal and Aromatic Plant Sciences, 2000 Cited by 5 Related articles', '2000', 'Shukla Sudhir, Singh Neelam, SP Singh', 'Journal of Medicinal and Aromatic Plant Sciences', 'Central Institute of Medicinal and Aromatic Plants', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13234', 1, 'Emotion dynamics of public opinions on twitter', 'Journal', 'The suitability of the seeds of 134 cultivars/lines of chickpea, comprising 32 white and 102 black types, as hosts for C. chinensis were assessed in choice tests between eight and four cultivars. Five pairs of 1-to 2-day-old insects were released in each choice test chamber. An unsuitability index was computed based on olfactory attraction (recorded after 24 h), oviposition, adult emergence and mean development period. Five cultivars were identified with an unsuitability value above 43% in the eight choice test. Of the white cultivars, ICCV-10466, with low weight grain, had a 49.76% index of unsuitability value in the eight choice test and 58.71% in the four choice test. Among the black type, a medium weight grain with rough seed coat, ST-3-F5-311, showed a 77.84% index of unsuitability in the eight choice test and 78.38% in the four choice test. ST-3-F5-333 had an unsuitability index of 43.25% in the eight choice test and 48.28% in the four choice test. Both ICCI-DL-89421 and C-235 did not maintain unsuitability in the four choice test.', 'Host suitability of chickpea cultivars to Callosobruchus chinensis. TD Yadav, S Singh, AN Jha, S Yadav - Indian Journal of Entomology, 2000 Cited by 1 Related articles', '2000', 'TD Yadav, S Singh, AN Jha, S Yadav', 'Indian Journal of Entomology', 'Entomological Society of India', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
