('13367', 3, 'PGPR for sustaining crop productivity under salt stress', 'Journal', 'The effects of three commercial fungal rennet substitutes (Marzyme, Noury, Modilase) in the manufacture of Cheddar cheese from buffalo milk were studied. Flavour development and biochemical changes in the trial cheeses were compared with those of controls made with calf rennet during ripening at 8deg C. Cheese prepared using Modilase showed superior flavour as compared to those made using Marzyme or Noury rennet. The flavour development in all microbial cheeses was faster than in the controls. The biochemical changes in terms of glycolysis, proteolysis and lipolysis over 10 months of ripening were greatest in cheese made with Modilase. The titratable acidity, lactic acid, soluble protein and free fatty acids in Modilase cheese were 1.34, 0.074, 7.56 percent and 26.18 microM fat per g whereas the control sample showed 0.97, 0.72, 5.48 percent and 19.36 microM fat per g, respectively.', 'Effects of fungal rennet substitutes on flavour and biochemical changes in buffalo milk Cheddar cheese during ripening YK Jha, S Singh - Australian Journal of Dairy Technology (Australia), 1994 Cited by 3 Related articles All 5 versions', '1994', 'YK Jha, S Singh', 'Australian Journal of Dairy Technology (Australia)', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
