('13415', 0, 'Enhanced Visual Search Using Image Re-Ranking', 'Journal', 'Soya cheese slurries, prepared as described previously [Indian Journal of Dairy Science (1985) 38, 269], were analysed for proteolytic changes during storage at 30 C for about 1 wk. Disc electrophoresis showed 4 major bands initially with Rf values of 0.914, 0.816, 0.698 and 0.695; additional bands appeared after 4 days, their number and Rf values being dependent on the starter bacteria and additives present. At the end of storage, proteolytic patterns of all slurries were similar, regardless of treatments. Concn. of free amino groups (0.75 mg/g in fresh slurries) increased during storage, and was affected by agitation, culture, rennet, papain, pH control and incorporation of additives. The number of free amino acids in fresh slurries was 9; after 4 days, slurries containing Streptococcus lactis and S. lactis+ rennet contained 8 and 13 amino acids resp., mainly at concn. considerably higher than in the fresh slurry, and slurry containing papain had 8 and 11 amino acids on days 4 and 8 resp. The concn. of active-SH groups (expressed as mg cyst-HCl/100 g slurry) increased to 1.01 in unopened control, 2.11 in agitated control and 2.91 in slurry with S. lactis+ rennet+ pH control.', 'Factors affecting proteolysis in soy cheese slurries. S Kumari, S Singh - Indian Journal of Dairy Science, 1990', '1990', 'S Kumari, S Singh', 'Indian Journal of Dairy Science', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13416', 0, 'High pressure phase transition and elastic properties of ytterbium compounds YbX (X= O, S, Se and Te)', 'Journal', 'A field experiment was conducted during 1985-1988 at New Delhi, India to determine the N and P requirement of a pigeon pea-wheat double cropping system. Phosphorus up to 35 kg/ha increased the productivity of the cropping system. At this level its application to pigeon pea alone or half the dose to pigeon pea and the rest to wheat gave a higher productivity than the application of the entire amount to wheat. At 17.5 kg P/ha the productivity was highest when all the P was applied to pigeon pea. The response of wheat to N was restricted to 80 kg N/ha, and N applied to wheat had no residual effect on pigeon pea. Thus a fertilizer schedule of 20 kg N/ha and 17.5 kg P/ha to pigeon pea, and 80 kg N/ha and 17.5 kg P/ha to wheat was found suitable for a pigeon pea-wheat double cropping system. Authors\' summary. KEYWORDS: TROPAG| Triticum aestivum Cajanus cajan| Cultural Practices| sequential cropping| wheat| pigeon pea| fertilizer management| phosphorus| nitrogen| India| Delhi.', 'Nitrogen and phosphorus management in pigeonpea (Cajanus cajan)-wheat (Triticum aestivum) cropping system. SN Sharma, R Prasad, S Singh - Indian Journal of Agricultural Science, 1990', '1990', 'SN Sharma, R Prasad, S Singh', 'Indian Journal of Agricultural Science', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
