('13425', 1, 'Modeling evolution of a social network using temporalgraph kernels', 'Journal', 'Paneer is similar to co-precipitates in protein composition and chemical process of manufacture except that the latter is fat-free. Unlike low-, medium-and high-calcium co-precipitates, there are no reports on the systematic status of minerals in paneer. This work is an attempt to study the mineral status of paneer. Paneer was prepared from 3.5%-fat milk containing 0.02%(T1) and 0.05%(T2) calcium sulphate, 0.02%(T3) and 0.05%(T4) disodium hydrogen phosphate, and no added salt (T0), by heating to 82 C for 5 min and coagulating at 82 C with 1%(w/v) citric acid solution. Five replicates of milk and paneer were analysed for Ca, Mg, P and citrate content. Mineral content (mg/100 g) of milk was: Ca, 139.81; Mg, 18.62; P, 80.83; citrate, 289.46; and salt balance ratio, 0.43. Addition of 2.63 or 6.58 mg Ca and 3.47 or 8.71 mg P to raw milk before heating caused subtle changes in salt balance. The combined effect of added salts, heating and acidification brought about a dramatic change in the product characteristics, and reversible shifts in the colloidal to soluble phases of minerals during heating and acidification of milk. Calcium content (% w/w, wet basis) and salt balance ratios were 0.41, 0.50, 0.54, 0.40 and 0.40, and 0.61, 0.68, 0.74, 0.61 and 1.28 resp. for T0, T1, T2, T3 and T4 paneer. All the paneer samples could be classified as low-calcium paneer as in low-calcium co-precipitates (0.5 to 0.8% Ca). Increases in ratios of salt balance in T1 and T2 were due to a significant increases in Ca and P but in T3 and T4 paneer the variation was due to significant decrease in P.', 'Status of some minerals of paneer made from cow milk with altered salt balance. CD Mistry, S Singh, RS Sharma - Status of some minerals of paneer made from cow milk …, 1990 Cited by 1 Related articles', '1990', 'CD Mistry, S Singh, RS Sharma', 'Status of some minerals of paneer made from cow milk with altered salt balance.', 'International Dairy Federation', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13426', 0, 'Interaction Effect of Different Nitrogen and Seed Rate Levels on Sweet Sorghum Feedstuff', 'Journal', 'The farmers who cultivate drylands in India have traditionally followed subsistence agriculture, growing crops that show little response to inputs and management. A strategy has been developed at various Dryland Research Centres that produces high yields from semi-arid lands, laying stress on the efficient exploitation of climate, energy, natural resources, scarce finance and available technology. The suitability of land in terms of topographical features and dependable water sources is discussed together with the existence of efficient crops, such as sunflower, pigeon pea and sorghum, the establishment of a good crop stand, critical irrigation, and the use of intercropping techniques. Climatically efficient double crop sequences and intercropping systems for different dryland areas in India are listed. KEYWORDS: TROPAG| Sorghum bicolor Cajanus cajan Cicer arietinum Arachis hypogaea Glycine max Carthamus tinctorius| Cultural Practices| dryland farming| intercropping| rainfall| soil types| India.', 'Sustainable high yields from semi-arid lands. SP Singh - Indian Farming, 1990', '1990', 'SP Singh', 'Indian Farming', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
