('13481', 0, 'Simultaneous quantification of flavonoids Homoeriodictyol and Persicogenin in the methanol extract of aerial parts of two different species of genus Rhus by validated HPTLC method', 'Journal', 'Exploration Strategies for Model-based Learning 35 exploration sequences during the course of the game. The high cost of the exploration sequences diminishes in innite games for the limitof-the-mean utility function, which measures only asymptotic performance. However, these methods may fail for the discounted-sum utility function which takes into account also immediate rewards. The main role of the opponent model is to predict its behavior in the future. Choosing a proper class of strategies for modeling is essential for the success of the model-based strategy. If the model class is too restricted it will probably fail in prediction. On the other hand, a too general class will make the best response problem and the learning problem intractable. Often, there are many ways to model a given behavior. Therefore, general background information on the opponent, or its type, is important for discriminating among dierent …', 'Technion, Haifa 32000, Israel S Singh, T Jaakkola, ML Littman - Economic Theory, 1986 Related articles', '1986', 'S Singh, T Jaakkola, ML Littman', 'Economic Theory', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0),
('13482', 0, 'New report of a sweet basil leaf blight caused by Cochliobolus lunatus in India', 'Journal', 'Exploration Strategies for Model-based Learning 35 exploration sequences during the course of the game. The high cost of the exploration sequences diminishes in in nite games for the limitof-the-mean utility function, which measures only asymptotic performance. However, these methods may fail for the discounted-sum utility function which takes into account also immediate rewards. The main role of the opponent model is to predict its behavior in the future. Choosing a proper class of strategies for modeling is essential for the success of the model-based strategy. If the model class is too restricted it will probably fail in prediction. On the other hand, a too general class will make the best response problem and the learning problem intractable. Often, there are many ways to model a given behavior. Therefore, general background information on the opponent, or its type, is important for discriminating among di erent possible model classes. This paper concentrates on deterministic nite automata for modeling the agents\' strategies. The question of how the modelbased framework can be extended for more powerful agents remains open for future research. An interesting class of such agents is the class of adaptive agents. The framework described in this paper assumes a stationary opponent. Extending it to adaptive opponents is di cult and deserves further investigation.', 'A. Rubinstein. Finite automata play the repeated Prisoner\'s Dilemma. Journal of Economic Theory, 39: 83 96, 1986. TW Sandholm and RH Crites. Multiagent reinforcement learning and the iterated Prisoner\'s Dilemma. Biosystems Journal, 37: 147 166, 1995. Mitsuo Sato, Kenichi Abe, and Hiroshi Takeda. Learning control of finite Markov S Singh, T Jaakkola, ML Littman - Economic Theory, 1986 Related articles All 2 versions', '1986', 'S Singh, T Jaakkola, ML Littman', 'Economic Theory', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0