('13771', 6, 'Link prediction using social network analysis over heterogeneous terrorist network', 'Journal', 'Nyctanthes arbor-tristis Linn.(NO Oleaceae; Hindi-Harsingar, Parajita) is a small deciduous tree, with sweet-smelling, yellowish-orange flowers, which is grown in gardens and also found wild in the forests of Madhya Pradesh. The bitter leaves are used in Ayurveda for the treatment of rheumatism, sciatica and intestinal worms (Chopra, Nayar & Chopra 1956). Seeds are recommended as a diaphoretic and diuretic and for the cure of scurvy. Lal & Dutta (1933) did not find any alkaloid in the leaves as reported by earlier workers but obtained D-mannitol and a bitter, amorphous glucoside, mp 71, which was not investigated further. The isolation of an essential oil, benzoic acid, hentriacontane, B-amyrin and B-sitosterol from the petroleum ether extract of the leaves has been reported earlier by Sen & Singh (1964). Isolation of the flavonoid constituents A concentrated alcoholic extract of the leaves, on keeping in the cold, deposited D-mannitol, which was filtered. The mother liquor was extracted with petroleum ether and benzene. The benzene-insoluble syrup was diluted with water and repeatedly partitioned with n-butanol, thus concentrating the glycosidic constituents in the solvent layer. The dirty brown residue from the butanol extract was purified by dissolving in alcohol and precipitating the impurities preferentially with ether and petrol ether. Removal of the solvent gave a bitter, orange coloured powder. This was then treated with lead acetate in alcoholic solution and the precipitated lead salt filtered. The filtrate was freed of lead and worked up in the usual way to give the glycosides as an yellowish-orange powder.', 'Flavonoids of Nyctanthes arbor-tristis Linn SP Singh, S Bhattacharji, AB Sen - Bull Natl. Inst. Sci. India, 1965 Cited by 6 Related articles', '1965', 'SP Singh, S Bhattacharji, AB Sen', 'Bull Natl. Inst. Sci. India', 'nan', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0